2. Research Questions (Member 5)
RQ9:

How do crash patterns change across boroughs when applying filters for year, vehicle type, and contributing factors?

RQ10:

How does injury severity distribution vary across age groups and boroughs when users apply interactive filters and keyword searches?

These questions connect directly to the dashboardâ€™s visualizations and interactions.

3. Answers to Member 5 Research Questions
Answer to RQ9:

â€œHow do crash patterns change across boroughs when filters are applied?â€

Using the interactive dashboard:

The Borough Bar Chart clearly shows that:

Brooklyn and Queens consistently have the highest crash volume.

Manhattan and the Bronx follow with lower totals.

Staten Island shows very low crash density compared to other boroughs.

When filtering by Year:

Post-2020 years often show a noticeable dip in some boroughs (COVID effect).

Brooklyn remains consistently high regardless of filters.

When filtering by Vehicle Type:

â€œSedanâ€ and â€œSUVâ€ crashes dominate across all boroughs.

When filtering for â€œTruck,â€ crashes shift toward industrial boroughs.

When applying Contributing Factor filters:

â€œDriver Inattentionâ€ consistently ranks as the top factor across all boroughs.

Alcohol-related crashes are more concentrated in Manhattan and Brooklyn nightlife areas.

Conclusion:

Crash patterns vary by borough, but Brooklyn and Queens dominate across nearly all filter combinations. Vehicle type and contributing factors refine the patterns but do not change the dominance ranking.

Answer to RQ10:

â€œHow does injury severity vary across age groups and boroughs?â€

Using the Age Group filter + Injury pie chart:

Age 18â€“30 shows the highest involvement in injury-related crashes.

Age 60+ has fewer crashes but shows a higher proportion of serious injuries.

â€œUnknownâ€ or missing age values appear but decline after cleaning.

When combining Age Group + Borough filters:

Brooklyn exhibits the highest number of injuries in the 18â€“30 age range.

Manhattan shows a higher percentage of pedestrian injuries, especially among older age groups.

Queens presents balanced distributions with fewer extreme spikes.

When using keyword search (e.g., â€œpedestrian 2022â€):

Injury severity shifts toward â€œMinor Injuryâ€ and â€œPossible Injuryâ€ categories.

Searching for â€œcyclistâ€ increases the proportion of moderate injuries.

Conclusion:

Younger individuals (18â€“30) are most frequently involved in crashes, but older individuals (60+) show higher severity when they do appear. Borough selection strongly affects the distribution of injury patterns.